04725nam a22005655i 9780822383130DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223831307 a10.1515/97808223831302doi  a(DE-B1597)554610  a(OCoLC)1136337393  a(OCoLC)875691850  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1992.6b.M377 2001 7aPER0100302bisacsh04a302.2345222  aEC 2410qHBZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/20485:1 aMcCarthy, Anna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmbient Television :bVisual Culture and Public Space /cAnna McCarthy. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b32 b&w photographs, 15 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConsole-ing passions: television and cultural power00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Public Lives of TV -- tPART I : HISTORIES AND INSTITUTIONS Rhetorics of TV Spectatorship Outside the Home -- t1. TV, Class, and Social Control in the 1940s Neighborhood Tavern -- t2. Gendered Fantasies of TV Shopping in the Postwar Department Store -- t3. Out-of-Home Networks in the 1990s -- tPART II : PLACES AND PRACTICES Reading TV Installations in Daily Life -- t4. Shaping Public and Private Space with TV Screens -- t5. Television at the Point of Purchase -- t6. TelevisionWhile YouWait -- t7. Terminal Thoughts on Art, Activism, and Video for Public Places -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough we tend to think of television primarily as a household fixture, TV monitors outside the home are widespread: in bars, laundromats, and stores; conveying flight arrival and departure times in airports; uniting crowds at sports events and allaying boredom in waiting rooms; and helping to pass the time in workplaces of all kinds. In Ambient Television Anna McCarthy explores the significance of this pervasive phenomenon, tracing the forms of conflict, commerce, and community that television generates outside the home.Discussing the roles television has played in different institutions from 1945 to the present day, McCarthy draws on a wide array of sources. These include retail merchandising literature, TV industry trade journals, and journalistic discussions of public viewing, as well as the work of cultural geographers, architectural theorists, media scholars, and anthropologists. She also uses photography as a research tool, documenting the uses and meanings of television sets in the built environment, and focuses on such locations as the tavern and the department store to show how television is used to support very different ideas about gender, class, and consumption. Turning to contemporary examples, McCarthy discusses practices such as Turner Private Networks' efforts to transform waiting room populations into advertising audiences and the use of point-of-sale video that influences brand visibility and consumer behavior. Finally, she inquires into the activist potential of out-of-home television through a discussion of the video practices of two contemporary artists in everyday public settings.Scholars and students of cultural, visual, urban, American, film, and television studies will be interested in this thought-provoking, interdisciplinary book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspects. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383130zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383130423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com